    <segment id="1" parent="22" relname="span">
We have all made decisions based on our intuition.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="16" relname="span">  Without reason or cause we knew 
that the direction we were about to take was the right one or the wrong one.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="elaboration">  It was a 
feeling that had no basis what so ever.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="26" relname="span">  Intuitiveness also has its place in interface 
design. </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="20" relname="span"> The term intuitive, however, means different things to different users.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="5" relname="elaboration">  To some 
it means an intuitive user interface is one that users can figure out on their own,</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="8" relname="span"> but to 
Chris Brown (1995) an intuitive user interface in one that is easy to learn. </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="10" relname="antithesis"> This does not 
mean that no instruction is required,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="18" relname="span"> but it is minimal,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="10" relname="elaboration"> making it easy for users to pick up 
and remember.</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="17" relname="span">

Intuitiveness can be assessed by measuring the products learnability or familiarity.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="19" relname="span">  In 
other words, how quickly the products usage was grasped by initial users (Bacon, 
2004). </segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="14" relname="span">   Usability testing serves well in this capacity.</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="13" relname="means">  By using various verbal 
instructions researchers can test their interfaces on inexperienced users and determine 
its ease of use and learnability.  

</segment>
